Cebu Air, Hynix, Nanya Technology, Petron: Asia Ex-Japan Equities Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-07-19T21:51:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-19/cebu-air-hynix-nanya-technology-petron-asia-ex-japan-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Cebu Air Inc. (CEB)  : The Philippines’ largest budget
carrier said it flew more than 3.1 million passengers in the
second quarter, a 15 percent increase from a year earlier. The
airline is “on track” to achieving its target of flying 12
million passengers this year, it said in an e-mailed statement.
The stock sank 0.2 percent to 86.05 pesos.  China CAMC Engineering Co. (002051 CH): The state-
controlled contract’s net income in the first half rose 30
percent from a year earlier to 163 million yuan ($25 million),
according to a statement to the Shenzhen Stock Exchange. The
stock dropped 1.4 percent to 28.14 yuan.  Hynix Semiconductor Inc. (000660)  (000660 KS): Bidders for a stake
in Hynix will conduct due diligence for four to six weeks
starting July 25, Korea Exchange Bank, one of Hynix’s
shareholders, said in an e-mailed response to Bloomberg News.
The shareholders will receive main bids after the completion of
the due diligence, the bank said without giving an exact
timeframe. Hynix gained 1.7 percent to 23,350 won.  Manila Electric Co. (MER)  : The largest Philippine power
retailer reiterated an earlier plan to invest in a $1 billion,
600-megawatt coal-fired power plant north of  Manila , a stock-
exchange filing showed. The stock rose 1 percent to 274.80 pesos.
 Aboitiz Power Corp. (AP)  , a partner in the project, gained
0.3 percent to 32.50 pesos.  Nanya Technology Corp. (2408)  (2408 TT): Taiwan’s second-largest
memory-chip maker posted a sixth consecutive quarter of losses
on slowing demand for computers. Second-quarter loss widened to
NT$7.9 billion ($273 million) from a NT$1.1 billion loss a year
earlier, the Taoyuan, Taiwan-based company said in a statement.
The average of seven analysts’ estimates compiled by Bloomberg
was for a NT$5.3 billion loss. Nanya dropped 0.7 percent to
NT$7.11.  Petron Corp. (PCOR)  : The largest Philippine oil refiner
and the local unit of Royal Dutch Shell Plc won contracts to
supply the Power Sector Assets and Liabilities Management Corp.
with 8.34 billion pesos worth of fuel, the Manila-based state
agency said. The stock jumped 0.6 percent to 16.88 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
